{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_honeysuckle_ver01/data/sn87076554/00340580898/1958052201/0103.xml":{"full_text":"1\nTHURSDAY, MAY 22, 1958\nBeavers Win Tri-Meet\nXs Three Records Fall\nBluffton college won eight of 15\nevents in defeating Wilmington and\nDefiance in a triangular meet on the\nBC cinders last Wednesday afternoon.\nThree Mid-Ohio records were beat\nen and two others were matched as\nBluffton outscored their two oppo\nnents combined. Final score\nBluffton 81% Wilmington\nDefiance 18%.\nwas\n58 5/6\nthe 9:8\nto set a\nElbert Dubenion reached\nmark in the 100 yard dash\nnew century mark and rangy Hank\nNichols tied the pole vault and 120\nyard high hurdle records. Nichols hit\n10' 6\" in the vault and raced over\nthe hurdles in 15:6.\nWilmington\u2019s Morton burned off a\n50:1 second 440 dash to set a new\nleague record for the quarter. Fred\nHoward, Defiance, set the other new\nPirates Snap 880 Relay Record, Logan\nWins Four Events In Victory Over Ada\nVersatile Bob Logan swept four\nevents and the Bluffton Pirates broke\nthe school record for the 880 yard\nrelay as they nosed out Ada 59%\n49% May 13.\nLogan put in his best performance\nof the year winning his special\nties, the 100, the 220 and the broad\njump and adding a victory in a\nfield just developed, the 180 yard low\nhurdles.\nThe Pirate relay team of Logan,\nEd Niswander,\nTerry Marshall\ntance in 1:35:8,\nond below the\nyear\u2019s team\nRamon Lewis\nripped off the\ntwo-tenths of a\nmark set by\nand\ndis\nsec-\nlast\nJerry Kohli hit a personal high in\nthe high jump as he cleared the bar\nat 5' 10\". Records were not avail\nable to show whether this also set\na new Bluffton high school record.\nKohli tied for first place in the high\njump with Hindall of Ada.\nDon Zimmerman won again in the\nmile run, this time in 5:07:5. Ramon\nLewis, defeated by Logan in both\nsprints, saved another first place fo\nBluffton by winning the shotput.\nBluffton\u2019s other first place cafne ii\nthe mile relay as the quartet o\nUSED FARM\nEQUIPMENT\n2\u20141950 Massey-Harris 44\nTract##\niey-Harris Model\n4\u20141957 Oliver Super 55 Die\nsel\nI\u2014195Ferguson 30\n1\u201419 Fdrd Tractor\n1\u20148-rt. Massey-Harris Disc\n/I\u2014*94Ft. Massey-Harris Disc\n14\u00bbFt. IHC Wheel Disc\n1\u2014Allis Chalmers Roto Baler\n1\u2014o4-Row John Deere Planter\nBLUFFTON FARM\nEQUIPMENT COMPANY\n105 E. Elm St. Phone 260-W\nQuirV Recovery Electric water heaters are\nHere\u2019s why you should get this BETTER\nhot water service for your home .1\n150-DEGREE HOT WATER...\nsafeguards family health,\nrinses dishes cleaner,\nwashes clothes cleaner!\nSPEED water\u2019s heated\nas fast as it\u2019s used. Quick\nRecovery Electric water pjgal\nheaters are jet-speed fast!\n1\nSAFETY sffe as electric\nlight so safe you can\ninstall them anywhere!\nLONG TANK LIFE elec\ntrie units heat the water,\nnot the tank. Tanks never\nburn out!\nOnly Quick-Recovery\nElectric Water Heaters\nsupply 150-dogree hot\nwater with SPEED, SAFETY\nand LONG TANK LIFE.\nmark in the 220 low hurdles, sur\nprising Bluffton\u2019s premier pair of\nNichols and Marty Strayer with a\nBeaver victories were scored in the\n100, ^20, mile, high jump, pole vault,\n120 yard highs, and the 880 relay.\nTed Berkey won the mile, Dubenion\nthe 220, Strayer the high jump. The\n880 relay squad of Dubenion, Stray\ner, Schirich and Taylor turned in a\n1:30:6, their finest time of the year.\nThe many-sided Howard did prac\ntically all the Defiance scoring as he\nwon the broad jump and the low\nhurdles and placed third in the 100\nyard dash.\nWilmington reached up for a blis\ntering 3:29:6 mile relay, also one of\nthe fastest times recorded in the\nMOC.\nfTto\nConsider all costs\u2014thi\nmore than ordi\nsee your pl\nth\nNiswander\ndistance in\nReichenbach, Burkholder,\nand Lewis clipped off the\n3:48:5, a new team high for the year.\nAda\u2019s first places came in the high\nhurdles, discus throw, 440 dash and\n880 run. Runser won the hurdles,\nNichols the 440, Hackworth the 880\nand Gunn the discus.\nRawson Organizes\nLittle League Team\n44 Boys Report\nOrganization of Rawson\u2019s first\nLittle League baseball team has be\ngun and 44 boysreported for the first\npractice, Russell Neighswander, sec\nretary-treasurer of the sponsoring\norganization, said.\nThis year\u2019s squad is being spon\nsored by Rawson merchants, who\ncontributed $335 towards purchase of\nequipment and uniforms for the\ngroup.\non\nOnly 15 players can be carried\nthe first team but Little League\nshirts have been ordered for\nplayers who try out for the squad.\nall\nDean Cuppies is manager of this\nyear\u2019s team. Practices have been\nscheduled for Tuesday and Thurs\nday at 6 p. m.\nBeaver Netters Dip\nBG Frosh 4-3\nThe Bluffton\nextended their\ndual meets as\nBowling Green\nweek 4-3 on the college courts.\ncollege tennis squad\nunbeaten record in\nthey defeated\nfreshman squad\nthe\nlast\nDon\nvic\nand\nJohn Kraft, Emil Kreider and\nNussbaum all salvaged singles\ntories for Bluffton and Kraft\nKreider swept their doubles match in\nstraight sets to provide the margin\nof victory for the Beavers.\nUNTIL JANUARY 20, 1948, Cham\npaign county had the oldest court\nhouse in continuous use in Ohio, but\non that date the building burned\ndown. Now the county has a new\n$650,000 structure.\nTwo rtyltt Io Inttall\nanywhoro. Cabinet mod\u00bbl\nprovidoi oxtra work tpaco in\nkitchen or laundry. See\nyour plumber-dealer today.\nBetter Service costs no\nwater heating.\nber-dealer soon!\nOHIO\n[WER COMPANY\nCHAMPIONS in the Triplett Wom\nen\u2019s Bowling league which was re\ncently concluded were the Triplettes,\n(above), Betty Edie, Iva Trippie\nhorn, Marilyn Trippiehorn, Dossie\nMcCullough and Edith Augshurger.\nIndividual leaders (at right) are\nWilma Nenensch wander (1.) whose\nseries of 448 was the season\u2019s high\nand Marilyn Trippiehorn (r.), who\nhad the season high of 193.\nPirates Finish Sixth\nIn District A BGSU\nBluffton high school\u2019s sprinters fin\nished sixth in the district track meet\nat Bowling Green State university\nlast Saturday, fading away after sev\neral outstanding clockings in Friday\u2019s\nqualifiers.\nThe Pirates grabbed 14% points,\nplacing them behind Delta, Blue\nCreek, Paulding, Columbus Grove\nand Liberty Center. Liberty Center\nwas Iasi year\u2019s district champion\nwith the Pirates a close second.\nThe flashy Bluffton 880 relay squad\nearned a berth in the state finals as\nthey finished second to Blue Creek,\nwho won the event in 1:36:1, slightly\nslower than the all-time school rec\nord the Pirates had set earlier in the\nweek in a dual meet.\nBob Logan finished fourth in the\n100 yard dash, with Ramon Lewis a\nstride away in fifth place. Logan had\nfinished first in the qualifiers for the\n100 and Lewis had led the 220 men\nto the pole on Friday afternoon.\nLogan had been clocked in 10:2 for\nthe 100 on Friday but 10:6 was good\nenough to win in the finals. Lewis\u2019\nBeavers Trample\nONU And Defiance\nIn Three-Way Meet\nBluffton college took ten of 15 first\nplaces last Saturday afternoon as they\noverwhelmed Ohio Northern and De\nfiance in a triangular track meet at\nAda. Final score was Bluffton 87 -f\nONU 59% Defiance 11%.\nThe Beavers lost another first\nplace when their 880 relay squad was\ndisqualified because of an improper\nexchange. Ohio Northern was de\nclared winner although the Bluffton\ngroup came home far in advance.\nWillie Taylor won the 100 yard dash\nwith the Bears\u2019 versatile Lloyd Paint\ner finishing second. Elbert Dubenion\ncame off the bench to win the 220\nwith Taylor finishing second.\nOther Bluffton victories were\nscored by John Gundy, in the quar\nter. Ralph Molder in the half-mile,\nTed Berkey in the mile, Hank Nich\nols in the high hurdles, Marty Stray\ner in the broad jump, Gene Brown\nin the discus and Gene McMullen in\nthe shotput. The mile relay team\n(Gundy, Benner, Carter and Nuss\nbaum) won their event.\nNichols also added seconds in the\npole vault, high jump and the 220\nlow hurdles.\nPainter was the chief point getter\nfor the Polar Bears, with a first in\nthe low hurdles, second in the highs\nand a second in the 100 yard dash.\nBluffton swept all three spots in the\n880, with Nussbaum and Yoder follow\ning Molder to the tape.\nSchool Patrol\nReceives Honor\nThe 12-member Blluffton elemen\ntary school Safety Patrol was pre\nsented with certificates of merit\nMonday morning in a recognition\nceremony at the school.\nO\u2019Neil and highway safety\nA continuation of the safety\nthrough the summer was\nThose receiving certificates were\nJan Benroth, patrol captain Diane\nLuginbuhl, Ronald Lehman, Norma\nBucher, Loren Core, Tom Edwards,\nJoyce Eikenbary, Beth Balmer,\nBucher, Bonnie Devier, Gayle\nber and James Diller.\nTHE BLUFFTON NEWS, BLUFFTON\n23:2 in the qualifiers was matched\nby Paulding\u2019s Jim Connor, who won\nthe grand finale on Saturday.\nLast year Lewis won the district\n220 title and placed second in the 100,\nwhile Logan was third in both sprints.\nHigh jumping Jerry Kohli duplicat\ned last year\u2019s performance at Bowl\ning Green as he finished third in the\nhigh jump for the second consecu\ntive time. Lewis picked up another\npoint for the Pirates as he finished\nthird in the shotput.\n1.29\n2.19\nStepleton, principal,\nsuperintendent, and\nsixth grade teacher,\nthe presentation of\nMiss Meredith\nA. B. Murray,\nRobert Stratton,\nparticipated in\ncertificates signed by Governor C.\nWilliam\nofficials,\nprogram\nstressed.\nKen\nGer-\nAlternates, who also received\ntificates were Sally Emmert, James\nDillman, Karen Schmidt, Douglas\nHahn, Gregory Emans, Ann Bucher\nand Karen Mericle.\nLarge Catfish\nLanded At Quarry\nTwo large cat fish were among the\nbig catches during the past week in\nthe Fishing Derby at Buckeye Quarry\nlake.\nWednesday Roscoe Holmes\na six-pound channel and\ninto another big one that he\nLast\nlanded\nhooked\ncould not get ashore. Monday evening\nBea Lansing of Ada brought in an\neight-pounder. She was using a\nnight crawler as bait.\nOHIO\nSAVE AS MUCH\nAS 75%\nEND WRENCHES, value\n1.69\nBillings BOX-END\n5.79\nADJ. CRESCENT\n1.79\n1.79\nHACK MTS\n79c HACK S^WS, now\nValue HATCHETS, now\n98c\nHATCHETS, now ............._.......\n1.19\nCLAW HAMMERS, going at\n4.69\nTRUE TEMPER,non-slip\nCUSHION GRIP HAMMERS 3.69\n2.98 METAL LUFKIN RUL|T. 2.00\n1.49 EVANS WHITE TAIME RULE .98\n69c EVANS WHITE TAPE REPLACE\nMENTS ..............\u2014......7.......................... .39\n49c FILES, selection 1........... 25c\n34.95 SUNBEAM ADD-ATOOL BOX 28.00\n4.98 AUGER BIT SETS 3.98\n6.95 HAND DRILLS\nSharpening STONES--10c\n3.95\n3.69\nCLOSE-OUT\n98c CAR POLISHES, WAXES\nKOTE-A-CAR\nTRAILER HITCH _________\n2.19\ncer-\nFULTON TRAILER CPLG.\n69c CAR VENTILATORS\n4.98 TRAFFIC GUIDE---------\n2.49 EXHAUST PIPE ENDS\nJames Fisher Earns\nNaval Promotion\nmate\n.49\nDrenches\nREVERSIBLE RA^\n.69\n'HETS ........A 3.91\nWRENCH JK J9\nWENCIYE^ .98\n:nt\n1.49\nADJ. CRESi\nSPEEDER^ low as\n1.29\n1.25'\n7\nreached that rank\nMay 15. He has now com pic\nrates within a two year pci\nHe is presently stationed\nthe\nwhere he is in charge of checking all\nweather observations at the station\nand filing monthly reports to the ce\ntral bureau.\nUnder his new rate he will be duty\nforecaster and will check out all pilots\nbefore their flights to major bases\nin the United States.\nFisher has been in the Navy for\ntwo-years and has served at Bain\nbridge, Maryland, Norman, Okla\nhoma and Fallon, Navada. He is the\nson of Mr. and Mrs. Joseph Fisher,\nS. Jackson street.\nCOLUMBUS, OHIO is the largest of\nthe cities in the United States named\nafter America\u2019s discoverer.\nITS A FAC1\nHutch Raised rabbit m^at is one of\nthe Xiighest\navailable. It\u2019s\nial meats\nrested.\nAskJfor\nAMSTUtf RABBITS\nVat yourXavorite meat\ncounter\n4.29\n3.98\nONE LOT OF\nAfter 15 years we are getting out\nof the tool business to concentrate on\nothe